        <!-- Facts Section -->
        <section class="section" id="facts">
            <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; color: var(--navy); margin-bottom: 2rem; text-align: center;">Key Facts About Congress</h2>
            <div class="facts-grid">
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>The Great Compromise</h3>
                    <p>The bicameral structure was a compromise at the Constitutional Convention between large states (who wanted proportional representation) and small states (who wanted equal representation).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>Reapportionment</h3>
                    <p>House seats are redistributed among states every 10 years after the census. The total has been fixed at 435 since 1913 (except temporarily when Alaska and Hawaii became states).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>The Filibuster</h3>
                    <p>Only the Senate has the filibuster ‚Äî a procedural tactic allowing unlimited debate. Ending a filibuster requires 60 votes (called "cloture"), making it hard to pass controversial legislation.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>Staggered Senate Terms</h3>
                    <p>Senators serve 6-year terms, but elections are staggered so only about one-third of the Senate is up for election every two years, providing continuity.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>Non-Voting Members</h3>
                    <p>The House has 6 non-voting members representing D.C., Puerto Rico, Guam, U.S. Virgin Islands, American Samoa, and Northern Mariana Islands. They can serve on committees but cannot vote on final legislation.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>Impeachment Process</h3>
                    <p>The House has the sole power to impeach (bring charges), while the Senate has the sole power to try impeachments. Conviction requires a two-thirds vote in the Senate.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>Revenue Bills</h3>
                    <p>All bills for raising revenue must originate in the House of Representatives. This gives the "people's house" primary control over taxation.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>Treaty Ratification</h3>
                    <p>Only the Senate can ratify treaties with foreign nations, requiring a two-thirds majority vote. This gives the Senate significant influence over foreign policy.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="fact-card">
                    <h3>Vice President's Role</h3>
                    <p>The Vice President serves as President of the Senate but only votes to break ties. The Senate elects a President Pro Tempore (usually the longest-serving member of the majority party) to preside in the VP's absence.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>

